snippet.textDisplay: I'd like to pose a Question, Caroline was charged with assault having reportedly hit him with a phone then attacked him with a lamp, violence so severe that he dialled 999, her boyfriend screamed out, as the police took her away 'I was normal until I met her' her former fiancé Andrew Brady tweeted in response to this 'Is it sad that I'm not surprised by this' under the heading 'Abuse has no gender', commenting further 'I escaped a very toxic situation' she also had him sign a confidentiality agreement upon their breakup. Now imagine these were the actions of her boyfriend towards her and his former girlfriend had made similar accusations of abuse, then he killed himself before the trial, would you feel the same about him? Would there be the same outpouring of Celebrity grief if Dermot O'Leary had hit his wife with a phone then beat her with a lamp, would we have a petition for Dermot's law? For a wife beater who's former partner had alluded to similar abuse? I have no hate for Caroline and her death is a tragedy which seems so wasteful, is fame so important you can't face living without it? If someone draws blood the police have to investigate it, what if next time she'd done more damage or accidentally killed him, then the police would be blamed for their inaction. Its a truly sad situation in which a lot of people have been emotionally devastated but it also highlights the selfishness of suicide and the destroyed lives that are left behind, but that's another debate.

snippet.textDisplay:
Although Caroline was a celebrity she was first and foremost a human being like the rest of us. It is so easy for your mind to take control over your thoughts, feelings and actions when you face knock after knock. Unless you’ve experienced first hand what it’s like to desperately want the pain, hurt and nightmare you’re trapped in to permanently go away you will never understand why people like Caroline end their life. It’s not about feeling weak or giving up, it’s about not wanting to face reality any longer. Caroline had a choice just like every other person who takes their own life. She made the choice to end her nightmare and suffering for good. Now she no longer has to suffer - she is finally at peace. My heart goes out to Caroline and her loved ones.
Sleep tight Caroline 💗

snippet.textDisplay:
😪 That was a fitting tribute. Caroline was such a talented lady whose warm heart shone through in everything she did. She clearly had her struggles but It is incredibly sad she felt she had no other option in life. She was clearly loved by friends & family, who I know will be filled with thoughts of "if only I......" and it will tie you up in knots. But Caroline's struggle this time was about a very specific thing and she probably felt she was drowning with dark times coming, I don't believe she died not knowing how much she was loved.

I don't believe shows like Love Island are
directly to blame for the tragedies it has been linked to. So many are fame hungry & underestimate what a life under the spotlight is like with the scrutiny of peers, media, fans & critics. That can be overwhelming & devastating for some & we live in a world of constant contact & so it can feel like theres no escape.

snippet.textDisplay:
It isn't cowardice that makes a person end their own life.
It's an inability to see a way to keep going on.
And it isn't cowardice that leaves a person unable to see a way forward.
Usually it's pain & fear.
We're normally sympathetic to others who are suffering.
Caroline deserved more sympathy when alive.
She still deserves it now, but moreso, her family deserve it now.
Be kind.

snippet.textDisplay: Every single person that has said "well she committed a crime" or "she deserved criticism for her actions" There's no way she deserved criticism at all. When did it become a free for all to destroy someone for a mistake? I agree there were questions for her to answer, and that is the only thing that should have been reported on. Social media is a cancer, gives people voices who don't deserve one, people who will post RIP to a dead celebrity and then the next week bully some teenager from behind a screen, telling them they're fat, worthless, ugly or some other derogatory term. I had a incident 3 years ago, ok I never suffered 10% of what Caroline did in hatred. But comments stick with you. I never broke the law, I never hurt anybody. It was an embarrassing incident that eventually everyone knew about. I still get comments about it now, but if I was famous I'd hear 1000 times more comments about it until the day I die. Fame comes with drawbacks and downsides, yes, but destroying your mental health shouldn't be one of them. A famous person is just someone trying to make the best life they can for themselves. Anyone who disagrees with me, just stop and think, you're actually saying, anyone who makes a mistake deserves people on social media coming along and telling you to kill yourself. The double standards you people have are pathetic. Caroline could have been your Daughter, Sister, Aunt, Cousin. If your child had a fight with another at school, and then all the other kids turned on yours, would you say to your Son/Daughter "suck it up kid, you made your bed now lay in it"? Of course you fucking wouldn't. Anonymous bullies and social media have a lot to answer for. Caroline did have some questions to answer, but because she did doesn't mean she should be bullied into suicide. I never watched her on TV but having suffered vilification myself for an incident it's really struck a chord with me. Like I say didn't know of or watch her on TV but because of the situation with the domestic abuse case, doesn't mean I want to see her bullied and told to kill herself by people who know nothing about the situation.

snippet.textDisplay: Well said Laura.  We will never really know why Caroline decided to end her life.  The pending court case would have probably found her guilty with a custodial sentence and then what of the future ? Criminal record, no work, no prospects, just obscurity.  My guess is that was never going to do for het.  The sadness thing is,  it would seem that she never really believed in and had enough faith in her so called friends and her experience of humanity as a whole.  Perhaps that is a consequence of the media world she worked and lived in.  The modern world is a dead world because none of us can truly live any kind of meaningful life without what is essential.  And what is essential is always invisible and gets lost in the glitter and noise of the party crowd.  In a sense we are all casualties of the age and times in which we find ourselves.  Caroline decided she couldn't go on. Given another time and another place, she would have made it.  Her loss won't change the emptiness of our modern and materialistic society and therein lies the pity.
